{
  "texts": [
    "Like Touretzky, Gardner McClune & Seahorn (2022), we see the construction of computational artifacts of AI/ML-based applications as a premier opportunity for students to see themselves as \"not just programmers, but AI application developers.\"",
    "While K-12 computing education research (CER) has recognized youth potential for consequential computational action with a variety of curricular activities and programmable tools, much less is known about what this means in the context of developing applications involving AI/ML.",
    "In this symposium, we bring together an international group of presenters who will address different dimensions of what learners can gain from designing AI/ML applications, examine in which ways critical agency can be developed, and what kind of challenges they observed.",
    "The presentations in this symposium will focus on a set of intersecting ideas:",
    "• Tools: What kind of tools already exist or need to be designed to support creative AI design activities?"
  ]
}